post_text:
PARAPROFESSIONAL NEEDED

The Gwinn Area Community Schools is seeking candidates for one (1) full-time LRE paraprofessional position at Gwinn Middle/High School. Position is 6.75 hours/day with a starting pay of $11.42/hour. Applicants must meet all school board requirements and pass a criminal background check.

Qualified candidates must have earned at least 60 credits at an institution of higher education; or obtained an associate’s (or higher) degree; or passed the MTTC Basic Skills Test and/or the required parts of the WorkKeys Assessment.

Interested candidates should apply by submitting a letter of interest and completed application (available at www.gwinn.k12.mi.us) to: Brad Pfluger, GMS/GHS Principal, PO Box 447, Gwinn, MI 49841. Applications are due Tuesday, September 8, 2020 or until position is filled.

GACS IS AN EQUAL OPPORTUNITY EMPLOYER

post_text:
First Three Weeks of School Reminders!

1. Monday, August 31st is the first day of school with a half day which means early dismissal for students.
2. There is NO school for any student on Friday, September 4th and Monday, September 7th due to Labor Day weekend.
3. Friday, September 11th is a regular in-person day of school for in-person learners due to the short week due to Labor Day.
4. The week of September 14th is the first full week of school.
5. Friday, September 18th is the first Flipped Friday for in-person learners. Flipped Friday means in-person learners are learning at home, not at school.

Please share!

post_text: Mrs. Sheltrow, GACS Teacher of the Year
text: Mrs. Sheltrow, GACS Teacher of the Year

post_text: Congratulations to Mrs. Nicole Sheltrow, our GACS Teacher of the Year! Mrs. Sheltrow has been a GACS teacher for 20 years and is currently a Title I teacher at Gilbert Elementary School. She is recognized for her leadership among her peers, her teaching strategies to increase student academic skills, and her genuine compassion and high expectations she sets for her students. We surprised her today with a drive-by at the school! Pictured here are her children as well as several of her colleagues.
text: Congratulations to Mrs. Nicole Sheltrow, our GACS Teacher of the Year! Mrs. Sheltrow has been a GACS teacher for 20 years and is currently a Title I teacher at Gilbert Elementary School. She is recognized for her leadership among her peers, her teaching strategies to increase student academic skills, and her genuine compassion and high expectations she sets for her students. We surprised her today with a drive-by at the school! Pictured here are her children as well as several of her colleagues.

post_text:
POSITION OPENING

Teaching Position:
Part-time Early Childhood Special Education teacher

Qualifications:
Candidates must possess a Bachelor’s degree as well as appropriate Michigan teacher certification with any of the following:
a. An endorsement in both early childhood and special education
b. A major or minor in early childhood growth education or child growth and development
c. An endorsement with a designation of ZS (early childhood general and special education).

Candidates must also possess strong instructional skills in the core curriculum, strong classroom management skills and the ability to utilize instructional technology. The Board of Education may employ an individual with such alternative qualifications that the Board finds to be appropriate and suitable.

Application: Interested candidates should apply by submitting a cover letter, resume, teaching certificate and copy of college transcripts to: Mrs. Sandra L. Petrovich, Superintendent; 50 West M-35, PO Box 447; Gwinn, MI 49841.

Deadline: Friday, March 6, 2020

GACS IS AN EQUAL OPPORTUNITY EMPLOYER

Gwinn Area Community Schools is seeking candidates for one (1) part-time lunch server at Gwinn Middle/High School.

Position is two hours/day (11:30 am until 1:30 pm, Monday-Friday) with a starting pay of $11.35/hour.

Did you know? We are in search of a full time School Social Worker!

The Gwinn Area Community Schools District is in current need of a School Social Worker, a role which will entail providing a full range of services to students who need additional support. As a key member of our support team, the successful candidate will partner with school administrators, guidance counselors and teachers to develop and implement plans that provide specialized support for selected students throughout the course of the school year. If you are passionate about helping every student be successful, we encourage you to apply today. Check the posting at www.gwinnshools.org Applications are due Tuesday, January 21, at 4:00 p.m.

Gwinn Area Community Schools Board of Education Trustee, Glenn Boogren, resigned from his position effective January 14, 2020. The Board has thirty (30) days to fill this vacancy. The person appointed to the open seat will serve on the Board until December 31, 2020.

Those interested in filling the vacant seat should submit a letter of interest to Ashley Jenema, Board of Education President, via US mail (50 West M-35, PO Box 447 Gwinn, MI 49841) or via email (ajenema@gwinn.k12.mi.us). The deadline for letters of interest will be 4:00 pm on Friday, January 24, 2020.

For additional information, call Sandy Petrovich at 346-9284.

post_text: It will be a cold night tonight, December 10, 2019! For Wednesday, the wind chill may be as low as -28 by 7:00 a.m. according to the NOAA hourly forecast (www.noaa.gov , then click on local forecast in upper right corner). Though the temperature will be c-h-i-l-l-y it will warm up during the day. Know that our busses have heaters as do our schools. Students are always encouraged to dress w-a-r-m on these chilly days. Please contact your child's school if he/she is in need of warm clothing, warm outerwear, or boots. Wind chills are always taken into consideration when determining whether to have school, most often when wind chills get to -30 or -35 for an extended period of time. Please refer to our Snow Day FAQ on our website at www.gwinnschools.org for closure procedures.

post_text: We understand we are under a winter storm warning for Marquette County until 10:00 a.m. on Tuesday, 11-12, that could impact the eastern edge of our district. As of 3:00 p.m. on Monday, 11-11, we are not anticipating a school closure for Tuesday. However, we will not know for certain until Tuesday morning comes. Please know if school is in session the weather may impact our Apple and Rabbit bus runs. Drivers will attempt to make all stops on these runs and will also attempt communication with parents for those stops not accessible due to road conditions. If this occurs, these parents are welcome to bring their child to school. This decision should be determined by the parent.

Gwinn Area Community Schools have 4 buses up for bid.

2001 - 01B - 57,000 miles not sure about accuracy because the speedometer has been replaced. It will drive away under its own power however it does need a fuel lift pump and it will not pass state inspection.

2002 - 02C - 205,000 miles. It will drive away on its own power however it will not pass state inspection.

2002 - 02D - 180,000 miles has a blown turbo and should be towed away. Not recommend to try and drive under own power.

2004 - 04A - 207,000 miles. Will drive away on its own power however it does have a leaking radiator and the fuel tank does leak. Will not pass state inspection.

· Bids must be in by Monday, October 21st at 10am

· You may stop by the bus garage for inspection

· To talk with Neil during inspection you must stop by Friday, October 18th between 10am and 2pm

· After approval of bid buses must be removed from premises no later than October 25th

post_text: Regarding bus schedules, emails, etc. ... We converted to a new routing software system and have been working with the company to get the parent email pushed out. This should occur soon. However, this email does not tell you what time the bus will come but is information on registering for the transportation system. Once you are registered in the system you will have access to view your child's bus times. As there are minimal changes from last year, having your child to the stop at a similar time as last year, with 10 minutes ahead of time as always requested, should get them on a Gwinn bus. If your child is not picked up in the a.m., please call the school or bus garage at 346-3914 and we will swing back and pick up your child. Thanks for your patience as we roll out this system. Until then you may email Scott Leutz, transportation, at sleutz@gwinn.k12.mi.us and he will email you the schedule for your child. New students who have no time from last year can call the school, chat with a neighbor, or drop off your child if desired for the first day.

post_text: Help us keep our kids safe. Please share this!
shared_text:
Kent County Road Commission
August 22, 2019 at 10:36 AM ·

It's that time of year again - the yellow buses are back! Here's a reminder from the Michigan State Police what to do when you see them on the road. (Image: Grand Traverse)

- Prepare to stop when a slowing bus has its overhead yellow lights flashing

- Stop at least 20 feet away for buses when red lights are flashing, unless driving in the opposite direction on a divided highway

- Slow down in or near school and residential areas

- Look for clues-such as safety patrols, crossing guards, bicycles, and playgrounds-that indicate children might be in the area

- Watch for children between parked cars and other objects.
School buses are like traffic signals:
—When overhead lights are flashing yellow: Prepare to stop
—When overhead lights are flashing red: Stop
—When hazard warning lights are flashing: Proceed with caution

post_text:
Sauna in the Classroom - Last night, the Board of Education received information on the joint sauna project under construction in Mr. Nicosia's building trades class and Mr. Mottes' CADD classes. Mr. Nicosia led the informational tour that displayed the status of the projects with detail on how student groups applied classroom instruction to design and build a sauna and wood stoves.

From CADD design to building a material list, from framing to roofing, from plasma cutting to welding, these students are gaining hands-on experience in the trades and doing some amazing work. See for yourself in the pictures below and give them a like or a share.

For more information on these or next year’s projects, please email mnicosia@gwinn.k12.mi.us or jmottes@gwinn.k12.mi.us.

A shout-out to the students, staff and parents of the Gwinn Area Community Schools today as our middle school/high school went into a lockdown at the recommendation of the Forsyth Township police. This was due to an incident within the local community. We also put Gilbert School on lock down.

Staff and students responded immediately following our procedures to keep everyone safe. Thanks to any parents who may have heard about this incident in the news and allowed us to follow our procedures to ensure the safety of our students and staff.

We are a Gwinn Area Community Schools team.

post_text:
Michigan State University researchers recently released a study that outlines what we have been saying for a while—Michigan is not adequately funding its public schools.

According to the report, total revenue for Michigan schools has declined by 30% since 2002 when adjusted for inflation. This puts Michigan 50th in school funding growth.

Will you get involved and call your representative to let them know our kids deserve better? We sure will. Let's do this together.

Link to report: https://www.masb.org/msu-report-puts-mich-50-in-school-fund-growth.aspx
